notes:
Spec revision (lumen-zdq, 2026-04-11): the load_user example in this epic description predates the fluency validation. Under the revised grammar it should use {} for named-field variants and std/int.parse_i32 instead of i32.parse. Canonical revised version:

import std/io
import std/int

type User = { name: string, age: i32 }
type LoadError =
    | NotFound { path: string }
    | ParseError { line: i32, reason: string }

fn load_user(path: string): Result<User, LoadError> io {
    let contents = io.read_file(path)?
    let lines = contents.split("\n")
    let name = lines.get(0).ok_or(ParseError { line: 0, reason: "no name" })?
    let age_str = lines.get(1).ok_or(ParseError { line: 1, reason: "no age" })?
    let age = int.parse_i32(age_str)?
    Ok(User { name: name, age: age })
}

description:
NOT an RC aliasing bug as originally hypothesized. Deeper Cranelift codegen corruption.

Repro: with trim written as

  fn trim(s: string): string {
      let slen = len(s)
      let b = bytes.from_string(s)
      var start = 0
      var end = slen
      for _ in range(0, slen) { if start < slen { if is_space_byte(bytes.get(b, start)) == 1 { start += 1 } } }
      for _ in range(0, slen) { if end > start { if is_space_byte(bytes.get(b, end - 1)) == 1 { end -= 1 } } }
      return substring(s, start, end - start)
  }

and called from kitchen_sink (which defines many helpers including generics + actors), trim's second for-loop body compiles to wrong x86. Specifically, instead of 'call bytes.get; compare; maybe decrement end', the IR emits 'rc_alloc(0); rc_alloc(16); write tag 0; write payload ptr; cmp result to 1' — that's Some/Option-variant-construction IR, unrelated to anything in trim's source.

First for-loop compiles correctly in the same function. Only the second one is wrong.

Not reproducible in isolated minimal tests — requires the specific combination of preceding definitions/statements in kitchen_sink. Adding/removing a blank line in the source can flip the behavior (byte-offset-sensitive).

Ruled out:
- call_resolutions span collisions (checked, no collisions at generic-call sites)
- variant_resolutions span collisions (checked, no collisions)
- is_aliasing_method_call (added as a fix, did not help; reverted)
- My interp-span byte_offset shift fix (working correctly per its design)

Hypothesis: shared mutable state between compilations of different functions. Perhaps a cranelift builder/block context reused across module_fn compilations, or an AST that gets mutated during an earlier pass. Needs deeper investigation — this is latent and will bite other users of '`let b = extern_identity_conversion(s)' + multiple loops over b'.

Workaround: inline the conversion at each use site (std/string.trim does this).

Escape hatch for performance-critical code that wants batch allocation + single-shot free instead of per-value RC. Leverages Lumen's existing magic-sentinel (0x4C554D45) trick: rc_incr/rc_decr check the sentinel and no-op on memory that doesn't carry it, so arena-allocated memory is automatically invisible to the RC machinery.

## Surface

A scoped block swaps the allocator for its extent:

  arena {
      var xs: List<i32> = list.new()
      for i in range(0, 1000) { xs = list.push(xs, i) }
      // work with xs, strings, structs, etc. — all arena-allocated
  }
  // arena reset/freed here; pointers that escape are now dangling

## Runtime additions (runtime/rt.c)

- lumen_arena_new(initial_size: i64): i64 — malloc a bump region, return handle
- lumen_arena_alloc(arena: i64, size: i64): i64 — bump-allocate, grow on exhaustion
- lumen_arena_reset(arena: i64) — reset write pointer to base (keep region)
- lumen_arena_free(arena: i64) — release the whole region to libc free
- Thread-local 'current_allocator' pointer (see design note below)
- Existing lumen_rc_alloc checks current_allocator: if set, bump-alloc from arena WITHOUT writing the magic sentinel; else fall back to malloc + rc header as today

## Codegen

- New ExprKind::ArenaBlock { body } or Item::ArenaBlock (scope-like)
- Emits: arena = arena_new(initial); set_current_allocator(arena); <body>; clear_current_allocator(); arena_free(arena);
- Body compiles normally — every rc_alloc site routes through the arena without knowing
- Scope cleanup's rc_decr calls no-op on arena memory (sentinel absent)

## Design note: factor for future pluggable allocators

MVP has two allocators (RC-malloc + arena). The dispatch site should be a single struct/fn-pointer indirection so a future ticket can graduate it to a vtable without touching every call site:

  typedef struct {
      void *(*alloc)(void *state, size_t size);
      void *(*realloc)(void *state, void *ptr, size_t size);
      void (*free)(void *state, void *ptr);
      void *state;
  } LumenAllocator;

For MVP just two entries exist (rc_malloc_allocator, arena_allocator), and set_current_allocator takes a LumenAllocator*. That's the same implementation cost as a specialized arena pointer, but leaves room for pool/slab/mmap/user-provided allocators behind the same interface when a concrete customer shows up. Do NOT ship the vtable without a second concrete user — YAGNI — but keep the dispatch site factored as if we would.

## Safety (non-)properties

MVP deliberately doesn't analyze escape. If a user returns an arena-allocated value from the block, it's a use-after-free — same ergonomics as C arenas. Document it loudly. Later tickets can bolt on:
- ArenaBox<T> as a distinct type so leaks are type errors
- Full region types (would be a significant typechecker lift — file separately if needed)

## What's not in scope

- Nested arenas (sibling or stacked) — MVP: one active allocator at a time
- Cross-thread arena sharing — actors run cooperatively, no threading concern yet
- Per-allocation statistics / profiling hooks — file separately
- Arena as a value users pass around — just the block form
- User-defined allocators — reserved for a future ticket once there's demand

## Test plan

- tests/lumen/arena_basic.lm: arena { alloc + use + exit }, assert no leaks via test helpers
- Benchmark (not gated in CI): same workload with and without arena, verify the allocation-heavy path speeds up and total rss shrinks

## Why priority=2

No open ticket is blocked on this. It's a 'when Lumen is used for something perf-sensitive' feature. But the cost is modest (~1 session for MVP) and the sentinel architecture genuinely invites it — worth doing before the RC model calcifies further.

